  "prompt": "The current year is 2014. Why is this the 21st century and not the 20th century?",
  "response": "The 21st century and the 20th century are named based on a system where a century in the Gregorian calendar starts with the year ending in 01 and spans to a year ending in 00. Therefore, the 20th century started on January 1, 1901 and ended on December 31, 2000. \n\nThe 21st century began on January 1, 2001 and will end on December 31, 2100. Since the current year is 2014, it falls within the date range of the 21st century. This system for naming centuries isn't necessarily intuitive because it doesn't start with the year ending in 00, but this convention traces back to the way we number years: the first century AD started with year 1 and included years up to 100. Thus every subsequent century follows from there, resulting in 2001 starting the 21st century.",
